Like @clinton, I've been assuming any meant any too.  The clarification indicates that the question is intended to ask about attacks specifically *targeting* a nuclear facility.  So, that seems to mean: 
1) cannot be a target of opportunity (possibly this takes many phishing, extortion attempts out of the picture); 
2) indication of targeting is required - probably takes hactivist attacks out of the picture unless they disclose/publicize. One assumption I've had is that most hactivist attacks would not involve sophisticated software (eg. would expect garden variety viruses rather than something like Stuxnet) and that they'd be intending to show the facility is vulnerable rather than doing anything that might result in a nuclear accident.  Underlying assumption is that most of that sort, at least directed against NPPs, are intended to get people riled up about the plant and get authorities to revoke licenses.  Also that the perpetrators are more or less rational & not homicidal.  Not sure those last are good assumptions at all. Hmmm.  May be easier to ask what *does* count, given the clarification.  Korea Hydro&NP - not sure if the attackers were intending to target a nuclear facility - probably have to drop counting that one.  Ignalina (1992) would presumably count because of perpetrator intent.  David-Besse (2003) would not count because it was unintentional.  Would Stuxnet count as disclosed?  Probably...   I was also thinking that BlackEnergy malware infection of an NPP would count. (https://ics-cert.us-cert.gov/alerts/ICS-ALERT-14-281-01B )  But, since the attack targets ICSs generally, not specifically at nuclear facilities, probably that doesn't qualify either.  Yet...I think that it really *should*.   Not sure if I should now interpret this question as - will there be a Stuxnet-like attack or a claimed hactivist attack.  If so, need to drop forecast dramatically.  Dropping some for now.

